{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28aab787effeo1WSdYzFX3JSix","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d75549d5c0019Z4kMajKZv61xr","parts":[{"id":"prt_d7554a4f9001gHHqCfcahD23xr","messageID":"msg_d75549d5c0019Z4kMajKZv61xr","sessionID":"ses_28aab787effeo1WSdYzFX3JSix","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_b3b582adb85e40b095e76570","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: <h1 align=\"center\">\n2: <img alt=\"logo\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/logo.png\">\n3: </h1>\n4: \n5: <div align=\"center\">\n6: <img alt=\"license\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-lightgrey\">\n7: <img alt=\"test\" src=\"https://github.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/workflows/Test/badge.svg\">\n8: <img alt=\"codecov\" src=\"https://codecov.io/gh/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=QqIqDQ7FZi\">\n9: <a href=\"https://pepy.tech/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"downloads\" src=\"https://pepy.tech/badge/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n10: <a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"pypi\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n11: </div>\n12: \n13: ## Introduction\n14: \n15: `fastapi-pagination` is a Python library designed to simplify pagination in FastAPI applications. \n16: It provides a set of utility functions and data models to help you paginate your database queries \n17: and return paginated responses to your clients.\n18: \n19: With `fastapi-pagination`, you can easily define pagination parameters in your FastAPI endpoint functions,\n20: and use them to generate paginated responses that include the requested subset of your data.\n21: The library supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination.\n22: \n23: `fastapi-pagination` is built on top of the popular `fastapi` library, and it works with a wide range \n24: of SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks. It also supports async/await syntax and is compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n25: \n26: Features:\n27: \n28: * Simplifies pagination in FastAPI applications.\n29: * Supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination\n30: * Works with a wide range of SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks, including `SQLAlchemy`, `Tortoise ORM`, and `PyMongo`.\n31: * Supports async/await syntax.\n32: * Compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n33: \n34: ----\n35: \n36: For more information on how to use fastapi-pagination, please refer to the \n37: [official documentation](https://uriyyo-fastapi-pagination.netlify.app/).\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## Installation\n42: \n43: ```bash\n44: pip install fastapi-pagination\n45: ```\n46: \n47: ## Quickstart\n48: \n49: All you need to do is to use `Page` class as a return type for your endpoint and call `paginate` function\n50: on data you want to paginate.\n51: \n52: ```py\n53: from fastapi import FastAPI\n54: from pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n55: \n56: # import all you need from fastapi-pagination\n57: from fastapi_pagination import Page, add_pagination, paginate\n58: \n59: app = FastAPI()  # create FastAPI app\n60: add_pagination(app)  # important! add pagination to your app\n61: \n62: \n63: class UserOut(BaseModel):  # define your model\n64:     name: str = Field(..., example=\"Steve\")\n65:     surname: str = Field(..., example=\"Rogers\")\n66: \n67: \n68: users = [  # create some data\n69:     UserOut(name=\"Steve\", surname=\"Rogers\"),\n70:     # ...\n71: ]\n72: \n73: \n74: # req: GET /users\n75: @app.get(\"/users\")\n76: async def get_users() -> Page[UserOut]:\n77:     # use Page[UserOut] as return type annotation\n78:     return paginate(users)  # use paginate function to paginate your data\n79: ```\n80: \n81: Please, be careful when you work with databases, because default `paginate` will require to load all data in memory.\n82: \n83: For instance, if you use `SQLAlchemy` you can use `paginate` from `fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy` module.\n84: \n85: ```python\n86: from sqlalchemy import select\n87: from fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy import paginate\n88: \n89: \n90: @app.get(\"/users\")\n91: def get_users(db: Session = Depends(get_db)) -> Page[UserOut]:\n92:     return paginate(db, select(User).order_by(User.created_at))\n93: ```\n94: \n95: ---\n96: \n97: Code from `Quickstart` will generate OpenAPI schema as bellow:\n98: \n99: <div align=\"center\">\n100: <img alt=\"app-example\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/example.png\">\n101: </div>\n\n(End of file - total 101 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"<h1 align=\"center\">\n<img alt=\"logo\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/logo.png\">\n</h1>\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n<img alt=\"license\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-lightgrey\">\n<img alt=\"test\" src=\"https://github.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/workflows/Test/badge.svg\">\n<img alt=\"codecov\" src=\"https://codecov.io/gh/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=QqIqDQ7FZi\">\n<a href=\"https://pepy.tech/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"downloads\" src=\"https://pepy.tech/badge/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n<a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"pypi\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n</div>\n\n## Introduction\n\n`fastapi-pagination` is a Python library designed to simplify pagination in FastAPI applications. \nIt provides a set of utility functions and data models to help you paginate your database queries \nand return paginated responses to your clients.\n\nWith `fastapi-pagination`, you can easily define pagination parameters in your FastAPI endpoint functions,\nand use them to generate paginated responses that include the requested subset of your data.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.md","time":{"start":1775789975069,"end":1775789975081}}}]}
